<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1326,2010]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">
<taxonomicName authority="Kurbatov &amp; Mifsud &amp; Sabella, 2019" authorityName="Kurbatov &amp; Mifsud &amp; Sabella" authorityYear="2019" box="[199,345,1327,1350]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Faronus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rica" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[199,345,1327,1350]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Faronus rica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[353,444,1326,1351]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[353,444,1326,1351]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fiori" authorityYear="1913" box="[679,781,1326,1351]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Faronus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="siculus">
<emphasis box="[679,781,1326,1351]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">F. siculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with which many morphological characters are shared. It differs from this species on the basis of the following features: (i) protibia of male widest in the middle with mesal margin sinuate in distal half (cfr. 
<figureCitation box="[523,644,1398,1423]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12. 7, 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1535,1558]" captionTargetBox="[177,1402,224,1437]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[152,1435,195,1514]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. 7, 8—Aedeagi; 9, 10—protibiae of males; 11, 12—female telisternites. (7, 9, 11— Faronus rica sp. nov.; 8, 10, 12—Faronus siculus)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612810/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Figs. 9, 10</figureCitation>
); (ii) left side of median part of aedeagus pointed apically (cfr. 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 7–12. 7, 8" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1535,1558]" captionTargetBox="[177,1402,224,1437]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[152,1435,195,1514]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. 7, 8—Aedeagi; 9, 10—protibiae of males; 11, 12—female telisternites. (7, 9, 11— Faronus rica sp. nov.; 8, 10, 12—Faronus siculus)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612810/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Figs. 7, 8</figureCitation>
); and (iii) the highly modified 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[549,562,1433,1447]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">rd</superScript>
and 4 
<superScript attach="left" box="[638,650,1433,1447]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">th</superScript>
ventrites having a strongly raised open cup-shaped structure in the middle (on 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[303,316,1472,1486]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">rd</superScript>
ventrite) and a 90° raised lamina (on 4 
<superScript attach="left" box="[789,801,1472,1486]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">th</superScript>
ventrite) which fits into the cup-shaped structure and apically curved posteriorly (cfr. 
<figureCitation box="[518,613,1512,1537]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,2000,2023]" captionTargetBox="[173,1435,583,1906]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[152,1435,521,1976]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Abdominal ventrites (dorsal and lateral view): 1, 2—Faronus rica sp. nov.; 3, 4—F. siculus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612806/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Figs.1-4</figureCitation>
). Females of both species are impossible to discriminate on the basis of morphological features. Some morphological differences in the apical region of the telisternite were found and these are illustrated in figures 11 and 12.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1326,2010]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,397,1620,1645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Ecological notes.</emphasis>
The two specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kurbatov &amp; Mifsud &amp; Sabella, 2019" authorityName="Kurbatov &amp; Mifsud &amp; Sabella" authorityYear="2019" box="[654,800,1621,1644]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Faronus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rica" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[654,800,1621,1644]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Faronus rica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[806,895,1620,1645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[806,895,1620,1645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
were collected in November by sifting leaf litter under 
<emphasis box="[221,417,1656,1681]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Ceratonia siliqua</emphasis>
, in a valley system at 
<quantity box="[666,723,1656,1681]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="420" unit="m" value="50.0">50 m</quantity>
of altitude, along with numerous specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schmidt-Goebel, 1836)" authorityName="Schmidt-Goebel" authorityYear="1836" baseAuthorityName="Schmidt-Goebel" baseAuthorityYear="1836" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tychus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="opuntiae">
<emphasis box="[1254,1436,1656,1681]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Tychus opuntiae</emphasis>
(Schmidt-Goebel, 1836)
</taxonomicName>
. Wied Babu (
<figureCitation box="[592,662,1692,1717]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–6. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1261,1284]" captionTargetBox="[162,1410,186,1194]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[152,1435,155,1241]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–6. 5—Habitus of female, Faronus rica sp. nov.; 6—Wied Babu, type locality of F. rica sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612808/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) is a fine example of a river valley and creek. The area is rich in endemic species such as the National Plant for 
<collectingCountry box="[683,748,1728,1753]" name="Malta" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Malta</collectingCountry>
(
<taxonomicName box="[765,1053,1728,1753]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Cheirolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassifolius">
<emphasis box="[765,1053,1728,1753]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Cheirolophus crassifolius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) for which Wied Babu is the 
<typeStatus box="[1388,1436,1729,1753]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="420" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1326,2010]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1800,1825]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is dedicated to Yves and Patricia Rica, a French family residing in 
<collectingCountry box="[1269,1334,1800,1825]" name="Malta" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Malta</collectingCountry>
who are always very helpful and contribute financially for entomological research work carried out by the corresponding author in 
<collectingCountry box="[261,330,1874,1899]" name="Malta" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Malta</collectingCountry>
. They offered free accommodation to many delegates present at the 4 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1127,1139,1871,1885]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">th</superScript>
International Congress of Biodiversity held in 
<collectingCountry box="[392,458,1913,1938]" name="Malta" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">Malta</collectingCountry>
(
<date box="[477,752,1910,1938]" pageId="3" pageNumber="420" value="2017-11-13" valueMax="2017-11-16" valueMin="2017-11-13">
13-16 
<superScript attach="left" box="[543,555,1910,1924]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="420">th</superScript>
November 2017
</date>
) and thereafter, this provided the right opportunity for the present authors to do intensive field work and to discover the new species which we gladly and proudly dedicate to them.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
